# Icon Usage Guidelines

## General Rule: Minimize Icon Usage

**Do not overuse icons in page components.** Icons should be used sparingly and only when they add meaningful value to the user experience.

### When to Use Icons

- **Functional actions**: Icons that represent clear actions (e.g., delete, edit, save buttons)
- **Status indicators**: Critical status information that benefits from visual distinction
- **Navigation elements**: Menu items, breadcrumbs, or navigation controls
- **Data visualization**: Charts, graphs, or visual data representations

### When NOT to Use Icons

- **Decorative purposes**: Avoid icons used purely for visual decoration
- **Redundant information**: Don't add icons when text already clearly communicates the meaning
- **Page headers**: Page titles and descriptions don't need decorative icons
- **Informational text**: Status messages, descriptions, or metadata don't require icons

### Best Practices

1. **Prefer text over icons** when the meaning is clear from context
2. **Use icons consistently** - if you use an icon for one action, use it for similar actions
3. **Keep icon usage minimal** - a page should rarely need more than 1-2 icons
4. **Consider accessibility** - icons without labels can be less accessible
5. **Focus on clarity** - if removing an icon makes the UI cleaner without losing meaning, remove it

### Examples

❌ **Avoid**: Adding decorative icons to page headers
```tsx
<div className="flex items-center gap-3">
  <SparklesIcon className="size-6 text-purple-500" />
  <h1>Page Title</h1>
</div>
```

✅ **Prefer**: Clean text-only headers
```tsx
<div>
  <h1>Page Title</h1>
  <p>Description text</p>
</div>
```

❌ **Avoid**: Icons for informational status messages
```tsx
<div className="flex items-center gap-2">
  <CheckCircle2Icon />
  <span>Status: Published</span>
</div>
```

✅ **Prefer**: Text-only status when clear from context
```tsx
<div>
  <span>Status: Published</span>
</div>
```
